The XPS is studied to measure the surface composition and chemical states of MoS2 QDs (Fig. S5). The peaks at 162.08, 232.08, 286.08, 400.08 and 533.08 eV are generated due to the presence of S 2p, Mo 3d, C 1s, N 1s and O 1s in synthesized fluorescent MoS2 QDs, respectively. These results demonstrated that N, C and O elements are detected together with Mo and S, which originated from the precursors. Further, the presence of Mo and S was also confirmed with the high-resolution X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (Fig. 2
                        ). As displayed in Fig. 2a, the XPS spectrum of fluorescent MoS2 QDs shows two characteristics peaks at ~228.6 and 233.08 eV, which belong to Mo 3d5/2 and 3d3/2 of MoS2 QDs [44,50,51]. These results indicate that Mo exists in MoS2 QDs as the tetravalent oxidation state [44,50,51]. Furthermore, the peaks at 162.6 and 163.3 eV are confirmed that the existence of S 2p3/2 and S 2p1/2 orbitals in MoS2 QDs, revealing the −2 oxidation state of sulphur in MoS2 QDs (Fig. 2b). The peak at 236.18 was attributed to the Mo6+, and the peaks at 166.36 (2p3/2) and 169.08 eV (2p1/2), are perhaps ascribed to the S2O3
                        2− group (Fig. 2), which is due to the oxidation of sulphur at high temperature. The HR-TEM, XRD, FTIR and XPS data demonstrated that the fluorescent MoS2 QDs were successfully fabricated.
